The Big Picture: Cloud Run vs Docker Compose
In Docker Compose, services share a private bridge network (tesseract_net), so agents:8000 is invisible outside the host. In Cloud Run, there is no shared private network by default — each service gets its own public HTTPS URL (e.g., https://agents-abc123-uc.a.run.app). This means if you deploy as-is, the agents service would be reachable from the entire internet.

The good news: Cloud Run has two built-in mechanisms that solve Vuln 2 at the infrastructure level, without requiring you to write authentication code inside the agents service.


Fix 2 — Unauthenticated Agents Service (The Complex One)
This requires understanding two Cloud Run features, then a small code change in the gateway.

How Cloud Run protects internal services
Mechanism 1 — Ingress restriction (--ingress=internal)

This tells GCP's load balancer to reject all traffic from the public internet at the network level before it ever reaches your container. Only traffic from:

Other Cloud Run services in the same GCP project
Cloud Scheduler, Cloud Tasks, or Pub/Sub
Resources inside your VPC (if you add a connector)
...can reach the service. This is equivalent to keeping it on tesseract_net but enforced by GCP infrastructure, not Docker.

Mechanism 2 — IAM authentication (--no-allow-unauthenticated)

This requires that every HTTP request to the agents service includes a valid Google-signed OIDC token in the Authorization: Bearer header. Without it, Cloud Run returns 403 before your application code even runs. The token must be issued to a service account that has roles/run.invoker on the agents service.

Together these give you two independent layers: "wrong network → blocked at edge" AND "right network but no valid token → blocked by IAM."

The deployment commands

# 1. Create a dedicated service account for the gateway
gcloud iam service-accounts create gateway-sa \
  --display-name="Gateway Service"

# 2. Deploy agents as PRIVATE (internal + requires auth)
gcloud run deploy agents \
  --image=gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT/agents \
  --ingress=internal \
  --no-allow-unauthenticated \
  --region=us-central1

# 3. Grant gateway's service account permission to CALL agents
gcloud run services add-iam-policy-binding agents \
  --region=us-central1 \
  --member="serviceAccount:gateway-sa@YOUR_PROJECT.iam.gserviceaccount.com" \
  --role="roles/run.invoker"

# 4. Deploy gateway with that service account identity
gcloud run deploy gateway \
  --image=gcr.io/YOUR_PROJECT/gateway \
  --ingress=all \          # gateway IS public-facing
  --allow-unauthenticated \
  --service-account=gateway-sa@YOUR_PROJECT.iam.gserviceaccount.com \
  --region=us-central1
The code change in the gateway
When the gateway runs on Cloud Run, it automatically has access to the GCP metadata server which can issue OIDC tokens for any target URL. You need to update agents.service.ts to fetch and attach this token.

Install the auth library (already likely present given your KMS usage, but confirm):


# In apps/gateway/
npm install google-auth-library
Then update apps/gateway/src/agents/agents.service.ts:


import { GoogleAuth } from 'google-auth-library';

@Injectable()
export class AgentsService {
  private readonly agentsApiUrl: string;
  private readonly auth: GoogleAuth;
  private readonly isCloudRun: boolean;

  constructor(...) {
    this.agentsApiUrl = this.configService.get('AGENTS_API_URL', 'http://localhost:8000');
    this.isCloudRun = !!process.env.K_SERVICE; // Cloud Run always sets K_SERVICE
    this.auth = new GoogleAuth();
  }

  private async getAuthHeaders(): Promise<Record<string, string>> {
    if (!this.isCloudRun) return {}; // local dev: no auth needed
    const client = await this.auth.getIdTokenClient(this.agentsApiUrl);
    const headers = await client.getRequestHeaders();
    return headers; // { Authorization: 'Bearer <oidc_token>' }
  }

  async executeAgent(request: AgentExecutionRequestDto) {
    const authHeaders = await this.getAuthHeaders();
    return this.httpService.post(
      `${this.agentsApiUrl}/api/v1/agents/execute`,
      request,
      { headers: { ...authHeaders } }
    ).toPromise();
  }
}
The K_SERVICE environment variable is automatically set by Cloud Run on every deployed container, so this correctly switches between local (no auth) and production (OIDC auth) without any manual config.

Do you need to change the agents service code?
No — not for the core protection. The security is enforced entirely by GCP's infrastructure. Cloud Run rejects unauthorized requests before they reach your Python container. Your agents service code stays exactly as it is.

However, as defense-in-depth, you could optionally add a simple shared secret header check in the agents service. But with both --ingress=internal and --no-allow-unauthenticated in place, that would be a third redundant layer.

